    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Reading Scores</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Alan Singer letter sees no causes for celebration of this year's reading test scores in New York State, since inner-city minority children are still performing poorly even with intensive preparation (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Last year New York State schools were devastated by poor results on new fourth-grade reading tests. This year they are celebrating improved scores (front page, June 2). Both reactions were inappropriate.</p>
        <p>What the latest test results show is that when you prepare students for tests, they score higher; when you spend a year preparing them, you risk invalidating the assessment; and even with intensive advanced preparation, children from inner-city minority communities are still performing poorly.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Last year New York State schools were devastated by poor results on new fourth-grade reading tests. This year they are celebrating improved scores (front page, June 2). Both reactions were inappropriate.</p>
        <p>What the latest test results show is that when you prepare students for tests, they score higher; when you spend a year preparing them, you risk invalidating the assessment; and even with intensive advanced preparation, children from inner-city minority communities are still performing poorly.</p>
        <p>Higher standards, without additional resources, are no standards at all.</p>
        <p>ALAN SINGER  Hempstead, N.Y., June 2, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is an associate professor of education at Hofstra University.</p>
      </block>
